07530nam a22010455i 9783110707373DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107073737 a10.1515/97831107073732doi  a(DE-B1597)551468  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aHIS0270902bisacsh04aThe Mediatization of War and Peace :bThe Role of the Media in Political Communication, Narratives, and Public Memory (1914–1939) /ced. by Christoph Cornelissen, Marco Mondini. 1aMünchen ;aWien : bDe Gruyter Oldenbourg, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (VI, 294 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Early Modern and Contemporary European History ,x2629-3730 ;v200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tOn the Mediatization of War and Peace since 1918/19 -- tI. Visualization of War – Narratives of War -- tEuropean War Literature in a Transnational Perspective -- tWhen History Went Public -- tVisualizing the War -- tMechanical Vaudeville -- tII. Peace Illusions – The Media as Postwar Prophets -- t“Where Did the Fourteen Points Go?” -- tWoodrow Wilson in Europe: December 1918–February 1919 -- tAsserting Czechoslovak Authority in Slovakia -- tConceiving a “Just” Peace for Trentino -- tIII. From Hope to Disenchantment -- tThe Media and the Transition from War to Peace -- tMedia, Propaganda, and Revolution -- tThe Italian Paradox: The Italian Media and the Myth of the Mutilated Victory -- tDevastated Victors -- tIV. The Memory of Peace and the Media – National and Regional Contexts -- tVisions of Stability and Anxiety -- tThe Failed Exit from the War -- tWhen the Decline of Europe Turned Topical -- tThe Execution of Cesare Battisti -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the First World War, mass media achieved an enormous and continuously growing importance in all belligerent countries. Newspaper, illustrated magazines, comics, pamphlets, and instant books, fi ctional works, photography, and the new-born “theater of imagery”, the cinema, were crucial in order to create a heroic vision of the events, to mobilize and maintain the consensus on the war. But their role was pivotal also in creating the image of the war’s end and fi nally, together with a widespread, new literary genre, the war memoirs, to shape the collective memory of the confl ict for the next generations. Even before November 1918, the media raised high expectations for a multifaceted peace: a new global order, the beginning of a peaceful era, the occasion for a regenerating apocalypse. Likewise, in the following decades, particularly war literature and cinema were pivotal to reverse the icon of the Great War as an epic crusade and a glorious chapter of the national history and to create the hegemonic image of a senseless carnage. The Mediatization of War and Peace focalizes on the central role played by mass media in the tortuous transition to the post-war period as well as on the profound disenchantment generated by their prophesies.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCollective memory. 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspects. 0aMass mediaxSocial aspects. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xMass media and the war. 4aErster Weltkrieg. 4aMass Media. 4aMediengeschichte. 4aNachkriegszeit. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War I.2bisacsh1 aBernardini, Giovanni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoisserie, Étienne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBracco, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCau, Maurizio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCornelissen, Christoph, econ